   323‚Üí## [0.4.0] - 2017-12-24
   324‚Üí
   325‚ÜíThe changes in this release include cleanup of some obscure functionality and a more robust public
   326‚ÜíAPI designed to support bridges to other logging systems, and provide more flexibility to new
   327‚Üífeatures in the future.
   329‚Üí### Compatibility
   330‚Üí
   331‚ÜíVast portions of the Rust ecosystem use the 0.3.x release series of log, and we don't want to force
   332‚Üíthe community to go through the pain of upgrading every crate to 0.4.x at the exact same time. Along
   333‚Üíwith 0.4.0, we've published a new 0.3.9 release which acts as a "shim" over 0.4.0. This will allow
   334‚Üícrates using either version to coexist without losing messages from one side or the other.
   345‚Üí### New
   346‚Üí
   347‚Üí* The crate is now `no_std` by default.
   348‚Üí* `Level` and `LevelFilter` now implement `Serialize` and `Deserialize` when the `serde` feature is
   349‚Üí    enabled.
   350‚Üí* The `Record` and `Metadata` types can now be constructed by third-party code via a builder API.
   351‚Üí* The `logger` free function returns a reference to the logger implementation. This, along with the
   352‚Üí    ability to construct `Record`s, makes it possible to bridge from another logging framework to
   353‚Üí    this one without digging into the private internals of the crate. The standard `error!` `warn!`,
   354‚Üí    etc., macros now exclusively use the public API of the crate rather than "secret" internal APIs.
   355‚Üí* `Log::flush` has been added to allow crates to tell the logging implementation to ensure that all
   356‚Üí    "in flight" log events have been persisted. This can be used, for example, just before an
   357‚Üí    application exits to ensure that asynchronous log sinks finish their work.
   359‚Üí### Removed
   360‚Üí
   361‚Üí* The `shutdown` and `shutdown_raw` functions have been removed. Supporting shutdown significantly
   362‚Üí    complicated the implementation and imposed a performance cost on each logging operation.
   363‚Üí* The `log_panics` function and its associated `nightly` Cargo feature have been removed. Use the
   364‚Üí    [log-panics](https://crates.io/crates/log-panics) instead.
   366‚Üí### Changed
   367‚Üí
   368‚Üí* The `Log` prefix has been removed from type names. For example, `LogLevelFilter` is now
   369‚Üí    `LevelFilter`, and `LogRecord` is now `Record`.
   370‚Üí* The `MaxLogLevelFilter` object has been removed in favor of a `set_max_level` free function.
   371‚Üí* The `set_logger` free functions have been restructured. The logger is now directly passed to the
   372‚Üí    functions rather than a closure which returns the logger. `set_logger` now takes a `&'static
   373‚Üí    Log` and is usable in `no_std` contexts in place of the old `set_logger_raw`. `set_boxed_logger`
   374‚Üí    is a convenience function which takes a `Box<Log>` but otherwise acts like `set_logger`. It
   375‚Üí    requires the `std` feature.
   376‚Üí* The `file` and `module_path` values in `Record` no longer have the `'static` lifetime to support
   377‚Üí    integration with other logging frameworks that don't provide a `'static` lifetime for the
   378‚Üí    equivalent values.
   379‚Üí* The `file`, `line`, and `module_path` values in `Record` are now `Option`s to support integration
   380‚Üí    with other logging frameworks that don't provide those values.
   382‚Üí### In the Future
   383‚Üí
   384‚Üí* We're looking to add support for *structured* logging - the inclusion of extra key-value pairs of
   385‚Üí    information in a log event in addition to the normal string message. This should be able to be
   386‚Üí    added in a backwards compatible manner to the 0.4.x series when the design is worked out.
   388‚Üí## Older
   389‚Üí
   390‚ÜíLook at the [release tags] for information about older releases.
README.md
     1‚Üílog
     3‚Üí
     4‚ÜíA Rust library providing a lightweight logging *facade*.
    19‚Üí## Minimum supported `rustc`
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí`1.68.0+`
    25‚Üí## Usage
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí### In libraries
    28‚Üí
    29‚ÜíLibraries should link only to the `log` crate, and use the provided macros to
    30‚Üílog whatever information will be useful to downstream consumers:
    58‚Üí### In executables
    59‚Üí
    60‚ÜíIn order to produce log output, executables have to use a logger implementation compatible with the facade.
    61‚ÜíThere are many available implementations to choose from, here are some options:
   106‚Üí## Structured logging
